    <a href="#" name="Other Features"></a>
    <h3 style="margin-top: 30px;">Other Features</h3>
    <p>
        MyDeals has other features that are common across the entire application.
    </p>

    <h4>Business Rules</h4>
    <p>
        MyDeals has trigger points in the code where custom business rules can be applied.
        Some of these trigger points are PRE_SAVE, POST_SAVE, PRE_ACTION, POST_ACTION, etc...
    </p>
    <p>
        These business rules come in 2 modes:
        <ul>
            <li><b>Validation:</b> These rules return a true/false and does NOT alter data. It is used for decisions.</li>
            <li><b>Action:</b> These rules perform a validation step and the actions against the data depending on the true/false response.</li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
        An example of a business rule would be:
        <ul>
            During a Save and Approve Action, if the ECAP Price decreases... save the deal, redeal it, alter various attribute values, version Rebate Strategy, cancel the approval and notify the user the deal was redealed and not approved.
        </ul>
    </p>

    <h4>Workflow</h4>
    <p>
        The Rebate Strategy and Deal Strategy Approvals follow a defined Workflow process.
        These workflows can change based on Deal Type, Role, Stage, Action and the user entered deal attributes.
    </p>

    <h4>Redeal</h4>
    <p>
        After Rebate Deals are created, changes can be made to the deals. These changes can come in two modes:
        <ul>
            <li><b>Minor:</b> Changes that do not require a re-approval. These are changes that do not alter rebate payments or Pricing Cost Test.</li>
            <li><b>Major:</b> Changes that do require a re-approval. These are changes that do alter rebate payments or Pricing Cost Test. Some examples are ECAP Price, Start Date, End Date, Total Volume, Ceiling, etc...</li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
        A Major change will initiate a redeal forcing the Rebate Strategy to change versions and allow changes to be made to the Rebate Strategy while not altering the current deal for downstream processing until the Rebate Strategy has been approved.
        Some other things to think about are redeals can split deals or replace deals, snapshot table concept controlling global or tracker based attributes, cancelling redeal and reverting back to previous version, etc...
    </p>

    <h4>Deal Types</h4>
    <p>
        Currently, all Pricing Strategies resolve into Rebate Deals. These Rebate Deals will be consumed by only 4 Deal Types:
        <ul>
            <li>ECAP</li>
            <li>Vol Tier</li>
            <li>CAP Band</li>
            <li>Program</li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
        Based on the Deal Type, the structure of the deal will be different. Some things that will be altered on the deal:
        <ul>
            <li><b>Attributes:</b> Different attributes and schedules above the standard deals will need to be managed.</li>
            <li><b>Rules:</b> Different Rules (Validation and Action) will need to be fired based on Deal Type.</li>
            <li><b>Workflow:</b> Approval Workflows can change based on Deal Type and Deal Sub Type (MCP, Tender, etc...).</li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <h4>Role Types</h4>
    <p>
        Each user is assigned to a single Role Type which controls Business Rules, Security and Account Assignments.
        Currently, the Roles Types:
        <ul>
            <li>FSE</li>
            <li>BMT</li>
            <li>RA</li>
            <li>GA</li>
            <li>MMBP</li>
            <li>FINANCE</li>
            <li>CBA</li>
            <li>LEGAL</li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <h4>Stages</h4>
    <p>
        Workflows approve and reject Rebate Strategies and Deals through stages.
        Currently, the Stages:
        <ul>
            <li>Requested</li>
            <li>Submitted</li>
            <li>Final_Approval</li>
            <li>Hold_Waiting</li>
            <li>Active</li>
            <li>Cancelled</li>
            <li>Expired</li>
            <li>Customer_Declined</li>
        </ul>
    </p>

